      <h1>Flamenco Guitar Capos</h1>
      <h2>What is a capo?</h2>
      <p>
        A Capo is a simple device which clamps onto the neck of your instrument in any position you choose. It shortens the playable length of the strings. It alters the pitch of the guitar  by half a step for each fret. Playing with a capo affects only the notes of the open strings. All other frets remain the same. Yet, the use of the capo can affect the tone of the guitar, creating a brighter sound.
      </p>
      <p>
       
The term is a shortened version of capotasto which is Italian for head of the fretboard.  Flamenco and traditional folk musicians use capos, less in classical and jazz world. That said, you will find specialist Classical guitar capos as well as those for Flamenco guitar. The capo is a simple way to alter the key of a song to suit a vocalist. You don't have to transpose the chords, and can make some complex arrangements easier to play.
      </p>
      
      <p>
        When two or more guitarists are performing together the use of a capo can create a more interesting sound and some striking effects. A partial capo can bar  some of the strings of the instrument. This creates many tonal variations without having to retune the instrument. A capo is a useful accessory for any Classical or Flamenco guitarist. It will open up many new possibilities.
      </p>
